Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to "settle down" in the city
2020-07-2605:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The natural ecology of the capital continues to improve, attracting wildlife cities to "settle down"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
(Reporter Wang Bin) Beijing Youth Daily reporter learned from the Municipal Bureau of Landscaping that in recent years, as the natural ecological environment of the capital continues to improve, the species and number of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals living in Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-class protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as national second-class protected animals such as impala, big swan, grey crane and mandarin duck.
Whether it is planted in the urban forests in the second ring road or the small wetlands embedded in the buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In midsummer, Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon dog was playing leisurely by the mountain stream, while two badgers were fighting each other.
Looking back, a wild boar could not resist the "scratch" on his body and was rubbing hard against the bark. According to Hu Qiaoli, director of the Management Office of Songshan National Nature Reserve, as of the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there are 178 species of wild animals, including the national first-class protected animal golden eagle and the national second-class protected animal spoon chicken and impala, and nearly one third of the wild animal species in the city can be found here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real 'masters', and our staff can only be regarded as the'bodyguards' at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the reserve on the spot, more than 30 professional patrol members patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and there will be a "big circle" every month and spend a whole day walking almost all over the reserve.
"During inspections, we should not only check and record biodiversity, but also check and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the increasing biodiversity of the reserve in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera, leopard cats, raccoon dogs and pig badgers have become "resident guests", and the "appearance rate" of the national second-class protected animals is also getting higher and higher.
According to Zhang Zhiming, director of the wildlife and wetland protection department of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now, and the number of wild animals in Beijing has continued to increase in recent years.
The appearance of wild animals in cities is becoming more and more common in recent years, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of the capital urban greening in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million mu started in 2018 proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of woodland and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature".
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green space, so as to facilitate wild animals to "visit relatives and friends". The trees planted are also the nectar and food plants that animals love.
Black soil "plants" agricultural modernization
Harbin, July 26, Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26, Title: black land "planting" agricultural modernization
In midsummer, two pesticide spraying planes passed over the 10,000-mu high-yield demonstration field in the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines. In the green field, the characters "the first field in the world" planted with black rice seedlings were particularly eye-catching.
Kong Lingqiang, director of the operation station, said that this kind of aircraft can spray chemicals on more than 6,000 mu of cultivated land a day, and the efficiency is about 8 times that of drone and hundreds of times that of manual work.
This farm is located in Youyi County of Heilongjiang Province, the largest grain-producing province in China. From the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of motors in the past, traditional Chinese farming and farms have changed in this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in modern agricultural production of Friendship Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural input and reduce pollution; On the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the standard operation level of agricultural machinery in the field.
In the process of rice production this year, the farm expanded the operation area of satellite navigation unmanned rice transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology can make the planting of seedlings more uniform, minimize the utilization of sunlight and arable land resources, and save 16 yuan in labor costs per mu.
The farm tried new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, and formed the largest agricultural machinery group in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total number of farm machinery is 49,00, and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field reaches 99.8%.
In agricultural machinery operation, 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100%.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture and digital agriculture are the direction of agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualian.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang Agricultural reclamation, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role in modern agriculture, and initially established a modern agricultural industrial system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production and industrialized management.
In the suburb of Youyi County, there is an agricultural machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 agricultural machinery and tools introduced and used by Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation over the years are on display here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of agricultural modernization in China.
give up a small family for everyone
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26 (Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26 th. Title: give up a small family for everyone-the mass transfer of Jiangkou River Lianwei in Hefei, Anhui Province
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu and Liu Xiacun
At about 4 pm on July 25, Fu Kunbao was wearing rubber shoes covered with mud and went from the front room to the back room, busy packing things back and forth with his wife Zhou Yan.
"After receiving a call from the village cadre to transfer, I was still weeding in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 mu of land and planted rice. Now he is growing well."I took medicine yesterday, and the tools have not been cleaned yet."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner."No one wants their home to be flooded, give up a small home for everyone."
In order to cope with the continuous high water level pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province, plans to use the Jiangkou River Lianwei where Fu Kunbao's family is located on the 26 th.
Jiangkou River Lianwei is located in Feixi County, close to the Chaohu levee.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yandian Township and Sanhe Township who need to be transferred.
As of 16:00 on the 25 th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, the fifth largest freshwater lake in China, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, 0.7 meters above the guaranteed water level.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen is clean, with a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table and eggs and some salt vegetables in the refrigerator.
"I did not expect to move it. The water in Jiangkou River looks good at the moment ."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some big things have not yet decided where to put them.
"When you clean up your valuables first. Large items such as refrigerators and TV sets can be temporarily put in the high-ground neighbors or relatives."
Wang Liwen, a village cadre, gave Fu Kunbao advice.
Wang Liwen was responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, and informed each household to confirm their resettlement plan.
The nearest resettlement site to Fu Kunbao's home is Su Xiao primary school in Yandian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the big items, Fu Kunbao and his wife also have a headache with more than 1,000 kilograms of grain and some newly bought furniture.
"The food is ready to be trailed to relatives."
As soon as the couple discuss, they put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 in the afternoon, Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
After 11:00 in the evening, the couple went back and forth at home, turned on the switch, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
"I hope the water will return soon."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9:30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Jiangkou River Lianwei that the local government had made various preparations before flood diversion.
