Church fire in Nantes, France: parish volunteers admit to arson
China News Agency, July 26. According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the famous St. Peter's and St. Paulo Cathedral in Nantes, France, was seriously damaged in a fire and the organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time in Nantes announced that a parish volunteer who was responsible for security in the cathedral had been charged with "arson and destruction".
He has admitted that he set the fire in the church.
According to the report, the local prosecutor Senas said that the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted that he had set fire in three places in the cathedral at night .
The lawyer of the person said that the arsonists now regret doing such a thing.
A few years ago, this person entered France through the way of refuge and was sheltered in the parish where the fire occurred and taken in in the church.
Prosecutors pointed out that recently, he tried to renew his visa and was in dialogue with the police.
But the church said it still could not believe that this normally very kind, smiling but quiet believer would destroy the church he loved so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18, the volunteer had already been questioned and investigated by the police because of the illogical problems in the narration, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters rescue at the scene.
On the evening of the 25 th, this person was summoned again because professional engineers from the laboratory of the Central Police Department in Paris obtained new evidence.
This time, the man admitted his arson.
According to reports, if convicted of arson, the suspect may face 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros.
According to the report, the fire caused serious damage to St. Pierre and St. Paulo Cathedral. The organ in the church was completely destroyed and the stained glass window behind the organ was also seriously damaged.
Brunet, chief architect of historic buildings in France, believes that it will take at least three years for the restoration of Nantes.
