FAA urgently ordered 2,000 Boeing airliners
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24 th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic aircraft registered in the United States. The reason is that the corrosion of the air check valves of the aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
The FAA said that it has received four reports of engine parking of the 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft so far, so it has made an emergency inspection request. The inspection targets are passenger aircraft that have been parked for 7 days or more and those that have been flying less than 11 times since they have been put into flight again.
The FAA warned that if the level 5 check valves of all two engines of the passenger plane are corroded, they may become stuck in the open position, causing the passenger plane to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the aviation operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into use again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of COVID-19 led to lower travel demand, and many passenger aircraft were sealed or used less."check valves are more likely to be corroded."
Boeing also said that it has advised aviation operators to inspect the aircraft involved in the directive and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that the major US airline operators usually fly many times in a day, but after the outbreak of COVID-19, a large number of aircraft were grounded; With the slow growth of passenger travel demand recently, some passenger aircraft have been put into operation again.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24 th.
The airline said in a statement that one of its passenger planes was on the way from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas on July 15, when an engine suddenly stalled and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine of the passenger plane and had inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines each said on the 24th that there was no engine stuttering associated with air check valves on their airliners.
Four American Airlines will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta said it would inspect its 20 passenger planes, but did not say whether there had been engine stalls.
Many media reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another impact on Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX passenger plane of Indonesian Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger planes were subsequently grounded around the world, stopped production in January this year and resumed production in May.
FAA director Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA had "made a mistake" in its supervision of Boeing for the 737MAX airliner.
