Tibetan antelope in Hoh Xil enters migration season
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Management Bureau that monitoring showed that Tibetan antelopes who had migrated to Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth one after another and began to return to their original habitat.
Monitoring images near the Wudaoliang Protection Station show that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three young Tibetan antelopes through the 3,002 kilometers along the Qinghai-Tibet highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge on the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. Tibetan antelopes have begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the relocated flock accounts for one fourth to one fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope colony.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early stage of the migration, Tibetan antelopes face a higher risk of predation, so the number of cubs in the sheep will be relatively small, and even there may be no cubs."
According to statistics from the Hoh Xil Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, director of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning is increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes returning is 4,860, an increase of 338 compared with 2018.
Lian Xinming said: "The migration of Tibetan antelopes is expected to end in early September this year, and the number of Tibetan antelopes is expected to continue to increase."
Tibetan antelope is a national first-class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan of Qinghai, Qiangtang of Tibet and Altun Mountains in Xinjiang go to Zhuonai Lake in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on Tibetan antelope protection in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of endangered animals), said: "The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a process in which the female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitats with their cubs after they have finished giving birth. At first, there are a large number of migration groups that leave the breeding land, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats along different paths according to different geographical populations."
In order to ensure the safe migration of the Tibetan antelope colony, the reporter learned that a few days ago, the Hoh Xil Management Office of Jiangyuan Park of Sanjiangyuan National Park has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and patrol in the main relocation areas.
If the Tibetan antelope sheep are found trying to cross the highway, the patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time, so that the sheep can safely pass through the wildlife passage and ensure that they are as little disturbed by human beings as possible on the way back.
