A new drug developed by the University of Australia is expected to be used to treat blood vessel blockage caused by COVID-19
Xinhua News Agency, Sydney, July 26 (reporter Chen Yu) Researchers at Monash University in Australia are developing a new drug to help prevent heart disease and stroke, and hope that this drug can be used to treat blood vessel blockage caused by Novel coronavirus.
Researchers have found that an enzyme in platelets accelerates platelet clotting before a heart attack or stroke.
So they developed a drug that can temporarily inhibit platelet clotting to avoid blood vessel blockage and prevent heart disease and stroke.
Researchers say the drug can only inhibit the clotting effect of platelets when there are signs of heart disease or stroke.
Since studies have shown that similar vascular blockage is one of the main causes of death in severe patients with COVID-19, researchers hope that this drug can be used in the treatment of such severe patients in the future.
At present, the drug has achieved good results in animal model experiments, and researchers are preparing for the next phase of human clinical trials.
The research results have been published in the American journal Science Translational Medicine.
