Employment and prices are generally stable
Economic Daily · China Economic Net reporter Lin Huocan
In the first half of this year, in the face of the impact of the COVID-19 epidemic, China made overall efforts to promote epidemic prevention and control and economic and social development. The situation of epidemic prevention and control continued to improve, the steady economic recovery was obvious, and the performance of employment and prices, which is closely related to people's livelihood was generally stable.
In the first two months of this year, the surveyed unemployment rate rose.
Especially in February, the production and business activities of many enterprises were basically in a state of shutdown, the employment demand of enterprises decreased, the recruitment was delayed or cancelled, and the surveyed unemployment rate in cities and towns increased.
With the gradual improvement of the epidemic prevention and control situation, the production and living order of the whole society has been continuously restored.
The Party Central Committee adheres to the general tone of seeking progress in the midst of stability, further strengthens macro policy hedging, comprehensively strengthens the policy of giving priority to employment, and actively promotes the work of assisting enterprises to stabilize jobs and expand employment,
China has stepped up policy hedging to stabilize posts, played a combination of policies of "reduction and exemption, slow back and compensation of three social insurance units to be reduced and exempted in phase, allowed to postpone the payment of social insurance premiums, and expanded the benefits of the policy of unemployment insurance for small and medium-sized enterprises for the benefit of the employment of key groups, such as subsidies for enterprises to absorb the employment of key groups.
With the implementation of various policies to stabilize employment, the employment demand of enterprises has steadily picked up, the employment situation has gradually improved, and the surveyed unemployment rate in urban areas has gradually decreased. In June, the surveyed unemployment rate was 5.7%.
Zhang Yi, director of the Department of Population and Employment Statistics of the National Bureau of statistics, said that in the second quarter, various employment policies continued to take effect, and the labor force that withdrew due to the impact of the epidemic in the early stage returned one after another. The urban labor participation rate in June increased by about 10 percentage points compared with February and was close to the level of the same period last year.
Data show that the total urban employment in June increased by more than 19% compared with February, and most industries reached pre-epidemic levels; The average weekly working hours of employees in enterprises reached 46.8 hours, 6.6 hours higher from February and 0.1 hours higher than that in January.
Prices are also related to millions of households.
In January this year, CPI rose by 5.4% year-on-year, setting a new high for many years.
In February, although the year-on-year increase of CPI dropped slightly, it was still in the "5 range".
The year-on-year increase of CPI is at a high level, which is not only driven by consumer demand before the Spring Festival, the wrong month of the Spring Festival and the low year-on-year base.
However, the COVID-19 epidemic has a particularly significant impact on prices,
Affected by the prevention and control of the epidemic, in January and February, there were delays in logistics, untimely supply of materials, and increased transportation costs across the country. In addition, some citizens hoarded and snapped up, and the prices of some daily necessities increased significantly.
In response to the disturbance caused by the epidemic prevention and control to the price situation, relevant departments have included important living materials into the scope of emergency transportation guarantee to ensure smooth transportation of materials.
Under the action of a series of policy measures, the market supply of vegetables and fruits has been strongly guaranteed.
In response to the rapid rise in pork prices at the beginning of this year, after the central government issued the policy of ensuring supply and stabilizing prices, various regions and departments quickly implemented it. The supply of pork reserves was significantly improved, the pig production capacity was recovered in an orderly manner, and the production and sales order was gradually normal.
Since March, pork prices have continued to decline and the year-on-year increase in food prices has dropped to 10.6% in May. In June, pork prices rose slightly from the previous month due to factors such as the slow down of pig production, the decrease in imports and the rebound of group consumer demand.
The seasonal changes in fresh vegetable prices were obvious, with an average increase of 3.4% in the first half of the year.
Affected by the high base of comparison in the same period last year, the price of fresh fruit continued to decline year-on-year, with an average decline of 13.3% in the first half of the year.
The basic livelihood of the masses has been effectively guaranteed, and the overall economic and social situation has remained stable and orderly.
With the gradual recovery of transportation and logistics, all localities have increased their efforts to ensure supply, and the market supply and demand situation has improved.
Since March, CPI has declined for four consecutive months, and the year-on-year increase has also dropped from 4.3% in March to 2.5% in June. The overall price level has returned to a stable level.
In the second half of the year, China's prices will continue to maintain a moderate level, and the overall inflationary pressure is not large, but it is still necessary to promote the restoration of production and living order on the premise of normalization of epidemic prevention and control.
We will effectively respond to natural disasters such as floods and droughts in major agricultural production areas such as grain, fruits and vegetables, strengthen market supervision, and resolutely crack down on activities that disrupt market order such as hoarding and driving up prices,
