Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sued the school after being compensated
2020-07-2605:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
After the playground was smashed, the children sued the school
Our correspondent Zhao Yifan
Xiaowen, 3, was accidentally hit in the head by Chen of the softball team while playing on the playground of a University.
After Chen made compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground was located apologize and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and mental damage.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net on the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled the appropriate security obligations, and Chen had made compensation, so the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen complained that he took Xiaowen to play on the school playground during the summer vacation in 2019, when the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risk, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents play in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then the softball team member Chen dropped the ball while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not meet the relevant safety regulations, and the team and related facilities are not effectively managed.
The school fault led to the above incident, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental pain, and also brought great pain to his family. The school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net on the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that entering the playground must keep a safe distance from the training ground and remind them to pay attention to their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school "failed to fulfill its security obligations", so he did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the site of the incident was open to the public free of charge by the university involved in the case. Although the school had a security obligation for the management of the playground, this security obligation only needed to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net on the playground, which has fulfilled the proper security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the previously reached compensation agreement. The two sides agreed that the dispute should be solved at one time.
After the incident, Xiaowen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, and there was no basis in the law, and the court rejected all the plaintiff's claims.
After the verdict was declared, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of the Tort Liability Law of China, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation of safety guarantee; In the case that the actions of the third party cause damage to others, the third party shall bear the tort liability, while the public place manager who fails to fulfill the security obligation shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place and foresee the possible danger and damage, so it is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the degree of damage, and the cost of avoiding and reducing the damage is the lowest. Therefore, the law stipulates that it shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified people entering the playground open to the public free of charge in the playground, the school should have the security obligation of the school should adapt to its social activities. Specifically, it should take basic safety measures and have the obligation of informing hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive security obligations on the managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled the obligation of informing, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for the infringement of the third party, even if the managers of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their security obligations, their responsibilities are also a supplement of damages. According to the newly issued civil code, after the managers bear the supplementary liability, they can also claim compensation from the third party,
Therefore, in this kind of accident, the victim should not expand the scope of claim after receiving the compensation from the direct infringer.
