Yang Hongnian, founder of Beijing Philharmonic Chorus, died at the age of 86
Beijing News (Reporter Liu Zhen) on July 26, Beijing Philharmonic Chorus published an obituary. Yang Hongnian, founder of Beijing Philharmonic Chorus, a famous conductor and music educator in China, a lifelong academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and a professor of the Conducting Department of the Central Conservatory of Music, died in Beijing at 13:55 on July 26, 2020 at the age of 86.
The picture comes from the official website of Beijing Philharmonic Chorus.
Yang Hongnian was born in 1934 in Nanjing, Jiangsu Province. He loved music since childhood.
In 1951, he was admitted to the Music Department of East China Normal University in Shanghai in the autumn of 1951. He studied under Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hizmann, and studied form and polyphony from former Soviet expert Arzamanov.
In 1958, he taught in the Music Department of Beijing Normal University of Arts. In 1973, he was transferred to the Composition Department and Conducting Department of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Chorus in 1983.
For more than 30 years, adhering to the tenet of "love and dedication", he has led the choir to sing all over the world and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has conducted performances of more than 30 groups including the Central Orchestra Chorus, the Central National Song and Dance Troupe, the Oriental Song and Dance Troupe, and the Shanghai Chorus, and held many symphonic concerts and chorus concerts.
His works include band training, chorus training, two songs writing, children song collection (first and second volumes) and his papers on Chorus intonation, on the sound level layout of orchestral music, as well as his works such as Chorus Orchestra and Debussy's harmony language. and so on.
Chongqing, July 26 (Reporter Liu Xian) The Chongqing Municipal Development and Reform Commission announced on the 26th that 4,404 fishermen have been retired in the city so far, accounting for 42.54% of all fishermen involved.
Li Daiguo, 53, said in an interview with China News Network that his grandparents had been fishing in the Longxi River. He has been fishing with his father since he was 11 years old. He has been fishing along the Longxi River, going up to Liangping, Chongqing, and going down to longevity. Every time I leave home, it is ten days and a half months. I rely on fishing to maintain my family life.
However, since 1997, as the rural population has gradually flowed into the town, there are more and more residents in Gaoanchang Town, resulting in more and more serious environmental pollution.
Paper mills, chemical plants and farms were built along the Longxi River, which also polluted the river.
By 2007 and 2008, Longxi River had become a smelly ditch.
"The scales of the fish caught are all black, and the inside is black when they are cut open."
Li Daiguo said that fishing is becoming more and more difficult after the river is polluted.
The local government began to make great efforts to control the pollution of the Longxi River, including cleaning, patrol, and aquatic resources management and protection.
Li Daiguo also retired from fishermen to production and became a member of the river patrol team to manage and protect aquatic resources.
Starting from January 1, 2020, Chongqing aquatic life reserve and related waters in the main urban area have implemented a comprehensive ban on fishing.
According to the data of Chongqing Development and Reform Commission, up to now, Chongqing has accumulated 3,403 fishing boats and 4,643 fishing boats have been signed to return to the fishing agreement, accounting for 63.3% and 86.3% of the total tasks in the three years respectively.
4, 404 fishermen have been retired, accounting for 42.54% of the total fishermen involved.
Among the 4, 404 retired fishermen, 4,267 were employment, accounting for 96.89% of the retired fishermen.
Pension insurance covers 2,691 people, accounting for 61.10% of the fishermen who retired from fishing.
