Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
2020-07-2604:56:44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
Israel strengthens prevention and control of the repeated epidemic
In the early stage of the outbreak of COVID-19, Israeli prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed in Israel, so it quickly closed all entry and exit ports, suspended non-essential industries, changed schools to online teaching, restricting public transportation and non-essential social activities, blocking cities with severe epidemics, and jointly maintaining prevention and control measures by military and police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of newly confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in Israel had once dropped to single digits in a single day.
Since June, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 has gradually rebounded.
Especially since July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, there have been more than 1,500 new cases in Israel every day for 8 days. As of July 25, the number of new cases on that day reached 916.
As of July 25, there have been 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
facing the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment places, and introduced a policy to restrict public transportation, stipulating that the number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17 th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictive measures, including the implementation of "closure of the city" on weekends, stipulating that the "closure of the city" will be implemented from 17:00 every Friday to 5:00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic service places will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people will be ban on all dates and period of time, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes are not allowed to eat in the hall, and only take out service is allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the severity of the epidemic, and failed to form a joint force with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government's prevention and control measures affected their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, believing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21 st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's ban on prevention and control measures such as restaurants and cafes and did not give corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not abide by the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters during outdoor activities. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chin or hang them on their wrists.
During the epidemic, the school was the hardest hit area for the spread of novel coronavirus. According to a reporter recent visit to the kindergarten, the teachers and students in the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the expert advisory group of the Israeli National Security Council on the fight against the epidemic, believes that Israel is moving towards a "dangerous situation" and pointed out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure and entertainment places and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to fight the epidemic, and the parliament and government departments should abandon their own interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on the fight against the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictive measures of different departments.
