The Lancet published an article praised China's anti-epidemic efforts to encourage countries to learn from the experience
China is a country with a population of 1.4 billion and a scale similar to Europe or the United States, and the COVID-19 epidemic has been effectively controlled at this stage, and there has not been a large-scale spread, which has largely controlled the domestic epidemic.
China has made a lot of investment in domestic research and public health construction in the past ten years, which makes China's preparation for COVID-19 much better than that of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
The author said that when SARS broke out in 2002, China was underprepared at first, especially the pathogen could not be identified.
When novel coronavirus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the virus species and shared genome sequencing data with the international community on January 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had clarified the clinical characteristics of the virus and warned the world about the threat of the novel coronavirus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research. Such research has been carried out very quickly and strictly through close domestic cooperation under the state of emergency announced in the Lancet in May and July respectively published the results of progress in the early trials of the COVID-19 vaccine developed by China in the Lancet.
Chinese experience shows that it is very important to invest in national health and research systems to effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for the country to respond quickly and effectively to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, especially low-income and middle-income countries, are worth learning from.
In addition, Chinese experience has proved that on the basis of strong research, a strong high-level decision must be made decisively based on scientific evidence, so that COVID-19 can be effectively controlled.
The article emphasizes that the government and its leaders must respect science, understand the value of science, and act on it in the most beneficial way to society.
